To analyze the change characteristics of the spatial agglomeration of interprovincial SLU levels, this study uses GeoDa software in calculating the local Moran's I indexes from 2002 to 2018 (Fig. 8
                           ). The Sankey charts of the local Moran's I indexes (Fig. 9
                           ) are also generated to show the mutual conversion relationship between various provinces in the four research periods (2005, 2010, 2015, 2018). The local Moran's I index classifies the spatial agglomeration status of the SLU level into four types: (1) H–H type (high value agglomeration areas with SLU level), (2) H–L type (high value areas with SLU levels surrounded by low value areas), (3) L–H type (low value areas with SLU levels surrounded by low value areas), (4) L–L type (low value agglomeration areas with SLU levels). Fig. 8 shows that the growth in the number of H–H-type provinces fluctuated over time. By 2008, the number of H–H-type provinces exceeded that of L–L-type provinces. This result indicates that H–H-type provinces can promote the SLU levels of surrounding provinces through industrial transfer, technology diffusion, labor migration, resource sharing, and enterprise cooperation and make them eliminate low-level path dependence. However, the number of L–H-type provinces is greater than those of H–L-type and L–L-type provinces. This difference is due to some provinces absorbing most of the talents, funds, resources, and other elements in the local area. Under the siphon effect, the opportunity for the SLU of neighboring provinces to improve is not available to the central province. Hence, a development mode with high center and low surroundings is formed, that is, a development mode with a high SLU level in the central provinces and a low SLU level in the surrounding provinces.
